# Playwright Fixtures

1️⃣ What are Fixtures in Playwright?
A Fixture is a reusable setup that prepares the test environment before a test runs.
Fixtures help to:
    1. Setup resources
    2. Share objects between tests
    3. Clean up after test execution
👉 In simple terms:
    Fixture provide test dependencies like browser , page , context , data or setup logic automatically to tests.

Example:
    def test_example(page):
        page.goto("https://example.com")
Here page is a fixture provided by playwright.

2️⃣ Why Fixtures are Important
Fixture help in :
    1. Reducing duplicate code
    2. Reusing setup logic
    3. Managing test dependencies
    4. Maintaining clean test structure
    5. Isolating tests
Without fixtures:
    browser = playwright.chromium.launch()
    context = browser.new_context()
    page = context.new_page()

you would repeat this in every test.
Fixtures solve this problem

3️⃣ Built-in Fixtures in Playwright
Playwright provides several default fixtures.
Common Built-in fixtures
------------------------
    Fixture & Description
    ---------------------
    1. page -> Browser page used for testing
    2. browser -> Browser instance
    3. context -> Browser context
    4. playwright -> Playwright instance
    5. request -> API testing requests
    6. browser_name -> Name of browser running test
    7. base_url -> Base URL configured in project.

Example:
    det test_login(page):
        page.goto("https://google.com")

    Here page fixture automatically creates:
        Browser -> Context -> Page
    
4️⃣ Fixture Lifecycle
Fixtures follow a lifecycle:
    Setup
    ↓
    Test Execution
    ↓
    Teardown

Example flow:
    Create browser
    Create context
    Create page
    Run test
    Close page
    Close Context
    Close Browser
Playwright automatically handles this lifecycle

5️⃣ Test-level Fixtures
These fixtues run for every test.
Example:
    def test_one(page):
    page.goto("https://example.com")

    def test_two(page):
        page.goto("https://google.com")
    
Each test page:
    New Page
    New Context
This ensures test isolation

6️⃣ Custom Fixtures
You can create your own fixtures.
Example:
    import pytest
    @pytest fixture
    def login_page(page):
        page.goto("https://example.com")
        return page
    
    Test
    ----
    def test_login(login_page):
        login.page("#username", "admin")
    
Here login_page is custom fixture

7️⃣ Fixture Scopes
Fixtures can run at different scopes.
Scope & Description
-------------------
1. function -> Runs for each test
2. class -> Runs once per class
3. module -> Runs once per file
4. session -> Runs once per test session

Example:
    @pytest.fixture(scope="session")
    def setup_data():
        print("Run once for all tests")

Scope helps in performance optimization

8️⃣ Fixture Dependency
Fixtures can depend on other fixtures.
Example:
    @pytest.fixture
    def login(page):
        page.goto("https://example.com/login")
        page.fill("#user","admin")
        page.fill("#pass","1234")
        page.click("button")
        return page
    
Test:
    def test_dashboard(login):
        login.click("#dashboard")

Here:
    Login fixture -> uses page fixture

So fixtures can be chained.

9️⃣ Auto-use Fixtures
Fixtures can run automatically without calling them in tests.
Example:
    @pytest.fixture(autouse=True)
    def setup(page):
        page.goto("https://example.com")
    
Now every test automatically starts with this setup.

🔟 Setup and Teardown using Fixtures
Fixtures can also manage setup and cleanup.
Example:
    @pytest.fixture
    def setup_page(page):
        page.goto("https://example.com")
        yield page
        print("Cleanup after test")

Explanation:
    Before yield -> Setup
    After yield -> Teardown
This is very common in automation framework


1️⃣1️⃣ Fixtures in conftest.py
Fixtures are usually placed in conftest.py so that all tests can access them.
Project structure:
    tests/
        conftest.py
        test_login.py
        test_cart.py
    
Example:
    @pytest.fixture
    def open_home(page):
        page.goto("https://example.com")
        return page

Now all test files can use:
    def test_home(open_home):
        pass
Not important needed.

1️⃣2️⃣ Playwright Fixture Flow
Typical playwright fixture flow:
    Test
    ↓
    Page Fixture
    ↓
    Browser Context
    ↓
    Browser

Hierarchy:
    Browser
    ↓
    Context
    ↓
    Page
    ↓
    Test

Each test usually gets a new context to avoid interference.

1️⃣3️⃣ Example Playwright Test using Fixtures
Example:
    from playwright.sync_api import Page

    def test_login(page: Page):
        page.goto("https://example.com/login")
        page.fill("#username","admin")
        page.fill("#password","1234")
        page.click("button[type='submit']")

Playwright automatically provides:
    Browser
    Context
    Page

1️⃣4️⃣ Advantages of Fixtures
Fixture provides:
    1. Code reuse
    2. Test isolation
    3. Cleaner tests
    4. Centralized setup
    5. Easy maintenance
    6. Automatic teardown

